I didn't log any because there was no point.  Quest has some bad design decisions at the core, so that it can't be truly fixed without removing them, which would require a complete rewrite.

For example, Quest is fundamentally based on internally referring to objects / properties by strings instead of using references.  While I can't name any consequent bugs offhand, it does lead to messiness (such as with the clone command), and makes it impossible to do static checking.


There's no concept of variable scoping.  For example, in code like
[code:2etmtk39]	command &lt;testloop&gt; {
		for each object in game {
			msg &lt;Setting quest&#46;thing to #quest&#46;thing#&gt;
			msg &lt;$testloop(#quest&#46;thing#)$|xn&gt;
			msg &lt;Afterwards, quest&#46;thing is #quest&#46;thing#|n&gt; }
	}[/code:2etmtk39], quest.thing is not guaranteed to be the same at the end of the loop (such as if testloop() has a loop of its own).  Constructs like that may appear in the code that prints inventory. 
There was also a related bug in a previous version regarding the interaction of exec / afterturn / dontprocess, but I don't recall the exact setup, so I didn't retest.



What does &quot;if A or B and C then ...&quot; mean?  Is it &quot;(A or B) and C&quot; or &quot;A or (B and C)&quot;?  Guess before running the below code.

[code:2etmtk39]	command &lt;testif&gt; {
		do &lt;testifp(T;T;T)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(T;T;F)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(T;F;T)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(T;F;F)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(F;T;T)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(F;T;F)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(F;F;T)&gt;
		do &lt;testifp(F;F;F)&gt;
	}
&#46;&#46;&#46;
define procedure &lt;testifp&gt;
	msg &lt;if $parameter(1)$ or $parameter(2)$ and $parameter(3)$ == |xn&gt;
	if ( $parameter(1)$ = T ) or ( $parameter(2)$ = T ) and ( $parameter(3)$ = T ) then msg &lt;TRUE&gt; else msg &lt;FALSE&gt;
end define[/code:2etmtk39]

Alternately, try [code:2etmtk39]command &lt;testif2&gt; if ask &lt;Q1&gt; or ask &lt;Q2&gt; and ask &lt;Q3&gt; then msg &lt;Accepted&gt; else msg &lt;not accepted&gt;[/code:2etmtk39].


